\section{Data Exploration}
\frame{
  \frametitle{Data Exploration}
  \begin{itemize}
    \item The data were collected every half an hour for each
      household.
    \item Each consumption series consists of 19008 observation or 396
      days.
    \item Depicted below are four time series chosen to illustrate the
      variability in the household consumption usage pattern.
  \end{itemize}
}

\frame{
  \frametitle{Data Exploration}
}
\frame{
  \frametitle{Data Exploration}
}

\frame{
  \frametitle{The Cramer Representation}
  In essence, The Cramer representation states that many time series can be
  arbitrarily approximated as a weighted sum of complex exponentials.\\
  When applied to real-valued series, the result says that many
  stationary time series can be approximated by a sum of the form:
  \begin{block}{Equation}
    $$
    x_t \approx \sum_{\lambda} A_{\lambda} \cos(\lambda t + \phi_{\lambda})
    $$
  \end{block}
}

\frame{
  \frametitle{Dealing with Non-stationarity}
  However, as we have seen in the exploratory section that our data is
  clearly a non-stationary one. Complex Demodulation is a technique in
  which trades frequency resolution for time resolution and allows the
  amplitude and phase to vary with respect to time. \\Thus we arrive at
  the following representation for a time series:
  %making some compromise.
  \begin{block}{Equation}
    $$
    x_t \approx \sum_{\lambda} A_{\lambda, t} \cos(\lambda t + \phi_{\lambda, t})
    $$
  \end{block}
}

\frame{
  \frametitle{Complex Demodulation}
  \begin{itemize}
    \item $y_t = x_t \times e^{-i\lambda_0 t}$
    \item $y_t' = \text{smooth}(y_t)$
    \item Then we can obtained the amplitude and phase from the $y_t'$.
  \end{itemize}
}


\frame{
  \frametitle{Complex Demodulation}
}

\section{An R package}
\begin{frame}[fragile]
  \frametitle{Package Description}
  To carry out the analysis, an R package was written and
  developed. The package container's two main functions:\\
  \vspace{5mm}
  \verb|mdemodulation| \qquad  for extracting the amplitude and the phase.\\
  \verb|mmodulation| \qquad for obtaining the filtered series $y_t'$.\\
  \vspace{5mm}
  Several other accessor functions are also available.

\end{frame}

